SIMPLE: flatten
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flatten
<hw>Flat"ten</hw> <pr>(fl⟦acr⟧t"t'n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Flattened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Flattening</conjf>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[From <er>Flat</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
reduce to an even surface or one approaching evenness; to make flat; to
level; to make plane.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To throw down; to bring to the ground; to prostrate;
hence, to depress; to deject; to dispirit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make vapid or insipid; to render stale.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To lower the pitch of; to cause to
sound less sharp; to let fall from the pitch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To flatten a sail</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
set it more nearly fore-and-aft of the vessel.</cd> --
<col><b>Flattening oven</b></col>, <cd>in glass making, a heated chamber
in which split glass cylinders are flattened for window
glass.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flatten</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flatten
<hw>Flat"ten</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become or grow flat, even,
depressed, dull, vapid, spiritless, or depressed below pitch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>flattened</ent>⟦br⟧
